													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='header' bgcolor='black' width='100%'>PALADIN STRATEGIES AND PLAYGUIDES</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='spti'>PALADIN DUELING TACTICS</font> - <small>Jarec Dracchenheart, Tarew Marr</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Guide to abbreviations:<p>
<p>
FOL = Flash of light<p>
<p>
* * * *<p>
<p>
One of the toughest things for any paladin to do in Everquest is to successfully win duels against other classes of similar level, and this is for two reasons:<p>
<p>
(1) We aren't the hardest hitters which leaves us disadvantaged against better melee classes(mainly warriors)<p>
<p>
(2) We have no real living attack spells(holy might is an exception) so we can be outdamaged by casters<p>
<p>
However by using reverse fighting tactics it is very possible for Paladins to win dueling situations, but it requires a lot of concentration and generally requires percision timing. I'll split the different tactics into sections based on the type of class:<p>
<p>
SITUATION 1: AGAINST A CASTER W/O a pet<p>
<p>
Winning against a pure caster without a pet such as a wizard can be extremely simple, however its also difficult at the same time. For casters without pets the real danger to a Paladin is being nuked. Therefore the best tactic to pull upon the opening of a duel is to cast flash of light on your target and get out of his sights, or if you are above 30, first stun your mob, then flash of light and finally root! This trio is an excellent way to render a caster vulnerable and then leaves them open to deadly melee damage. This may take some time to perfect but it is a great tactic..<p>
<p>
<p>
To prevent the caster from hitting you be sure to cast flash of light as often as possible to keep the caster blinded(rendering line of sight spells worthless) and to stun casters to prevent them from casting in the first place. Holy might makes this tactic much easier as the stun lasts much longer.<p>
<p>
SITUATION 2: AGAINST A CASTER WITH A PET<p>
<p>
Casters with pets will bring a whole new edge to a duel because you are dealing with two targets. If the caster is allowed to summon his pet beforehand then you need to switch tactics, however if he is not allowed to summon a pet before engaging in a duel, then the strategy in situation 1 should work fairly well. If the caster does in fact have a pet at the start of the duel or manages to summon one, remember that if you go after the pet, the caster will just nuke you. Pets should therefore be treated as distractions rather than open threats. The best way to deal with casters and pets is to take the caster out for a few seconds using stun, then root the pet and run towards the caster and start meleeing him. If they are smart the caster will run towards his pet and if he does, jsut root the caster, and melee him then. A rooted caster is an easy target so ultimately you should aim for that in order to deal with casters who get shadow step or invisible.<p>

SPECIAL SITUATION 2: NECROMANCERS WITH PETS<p>
<p>
Necromancers are the most dangerous ofthe casters for paladins to worry about because the dot and lifetap spells IMHO are far more deadly than just using DD because dots stack causing massive damage. One things that makes Necros particularly vulernable is that their pets are undead! And who are the masters of undead killing/fearing? Clerics and Paladins are so use that to your advantage. Once you get the necro(or shadowknight for that matter) rooted or stunned, you can either DD the pet or fear it. fearing it first is often a better strategy and puts the pet out of the picture for a bit allowing you to focus on your main objective.<p>
<p>
SITUATION 3: Warriors and other melee classes<p>
<p>
Warriors deal massive melee damage so a straight outright slash and bash fest is not the best way to go about it. It may seem odd but FOL is the best way to open up a duel with a warrior. FOLing a warrior means they can not see you and therefore can not attack you. Root is pretty much useless here except if you want to heal so don't use root unless you are going to heal. Stun spells also work well but don't waste time casting stun when flash of light will keep them blind, and thus unable to fight. A warrior without his sight is hopeless no matter how much HP or AC he has.<p>
---<p>
HEALING IN COMBAT TACTICS<p>

Knowing how to heal yourself in combat is a great benefit to your advantage because(and this is especially true with casters) ifyou can prolong a fight, your opponent will most likely run out of mana or stamina. For warriors, the safest way to heal is to stun, root and step back and heal.<p>
<p>
For casters its a different matter, because you must stun,root and then heal butby thattime stun will most likely have worn off, in which the only safe method of healing in this situation is to run for cover and heal BUT this is not advisable because most likely the caster will invis(if capable of) and meditate regaining all their mana. If Paladins got see invisible this would be less of a problem but we don't so ultimately its hard to heal with a caster around and even harder if a pet is present. Ultimately you should be concerned with disabling the caster so you can melee him to death, so healing should not be essential unlessthe caster does manage to get away in which case, then heal.<p>
---<p>
SPECIAL SITUATION: PALADIN VS PALADIN<p>
<p>
ah yes, the call of holy warrior versus holy warrior. Any class versus itself is hard to judge how to proceed and this is especially true with hybrids since both magic and melee MUST come into play. When its Paladin vs Paladin it ultimately comes down to equipment, pure stats and whether or not you are a lucky roller :-)<p>
---<p>
Arguably the one asset that allows a paladin to tip the scales in any fight is Lay of hands. This not only serves as an instant heal, but its also a psychological killer for your opponent, so you should ALWAYS have LOH in any duel.<p>
<p>
Safe dueling to all of the honourable and valorous paladins of Norrath!<p>
<p>
Sir Jarec Dracchenheart<p>
Holy Knight of Tunare<p>
Keepers of Knowledge Master Paladin of the 31st circle<p>
Tarew Marr<p>
<p>
I would be glad to answer any questions about how these strategies should be implemented so feel free to e-mail me at:<p>
<p>
JarecD@maelstrom.screaming.net<p> 

